The principle means **CSS should define all possible visual states** (active, hidden, dark-theme, error, etc.) while **JavaScript only decides WHEN to apply them** by toggling classes.

```css
/* CSS DEFINES the visual state */
.modal { opacity: 0; visibility: hidden; transition: all 0.3s ease; }
.modal.active { opacity: 1; visibility: visible; }
```
```javascript
// JS DECIDES when to apply it
modal.classList.toggle("active");
```

**Why it's best practice:** (1) Separation of concerns — styling in CSS, behavior in JS. (2) CSS transitions work automatically. (3) Easier maintenance. (4) Better performance — browsers optimize CSS transitions. (5) Reusability — same class works on any element.

`IntersectionObserver` is a browser API that **asynchronously detects when elements enter or leave the viewport**. You create an observer, tell it which elements to watch, and it calls your callback when they become visible.

```javascript
const observer = new IntersectionObserver((entries) => {
    entries.forEach(entry => {
        if (entry.isIntersecting) entry.target.classList.add("visible");
    });
}, { threshold: 0.15 });
document.querySelectorAll(".fade-in").forEach(el => observer.observe(el));
```

**Why it's better than scroll listeners:** (1) Performance — scroll events fire hundreds of times per second; IntersectionObserver runs asynchronously. (2) No manual position calculations. (3) Battery friendly on mobile. (4) Clean API with built-in threshold.

```javascript
const showNotification = (message, type = "info", duration = 3000) => {
    const notification = document.createElement("div");
    notification.classList.add("notification", type);
    notification.textContent = message;
    document.querySelector("#notification-container").appendChild(notification);
    requestAnimationFrame(() => notification.classList.add("show"));
    setTimeout(() => {
        notification.classList.remove("show");
        notification.addEventListener("transitionend", () => notification.remove());
    }, duration);
};
showNotification("Settings saved!", "success");
```

The corresponding CSS uses `transform: translateX(120%)` as default and `transform: translateX(0)` for `.show`, with a transition. `requestAnimationFrame` ensures the initial state is registered before adding `.show`. `transitionend` removes the element after the exit animation completes.
